        <div class="background-section">
            <h2>Background: Tariff Deadline Crisis</h2>
            <p>
                Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick announced that August 1, 2025 is the firm deadline for countries to begin paying new tariffs to the United States. The tariffs, as high as 50%, will affect dozens of countries. The comprehensive list targets a wide range of sectors, from raw materials like steel to finished consumer goods like electronics and apparel.
            </p>
            <p>
                Inside sources report a common theme from the negotiating table: national representatives consistently misjudged the administration's resolve, leading to widespread stalemates. Furthermore, initial hopes for broad exemptions have faded. In response, reports are emerging of key industry players, like auto-parts maker MagnaShift and tech firm Circuitron, beginning to move facilities. However, economists are puzzled by the relative inaction from the 23 unresponsive nations. An anonymous Treasury official warned, "It's as if they don't see the economic freight train that's about to hit them."
            </p>
            <p><strong>Current Statistics:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>46 countries affected by tariffs</li>
                <li>15 countries actively negotiating</li>
                <li>8 countries secured preliminary agreements</li>
                <li>23 countries made no contact with US</li>
                <li>127 major corporations have supply chain exposure</li>
                <li>45 companies found alternative suppliers</li>
                <li>82 companies still dependent on affected imports</li>
            </ul>
